The patient developed hepatic sinusoidal obstruction syndrome (SOS), also known as Veno-occlusive liver disease, after chemotherapy containing cyclophosphamide. The event is life-threatening (per narrative), meeting the criteria for seriousness. SOS is a well-documented risk associated with cyclophosphamide-containing regimens (Section 5.6 of RSI). Regarding the Naranjo score: 1. Previous reports of this reaction: Yes (+1). 2. Event appeared after drug administered: Yes (+2). 3. Improved after discontinuation/intervention: Yes (treated successfully with defibrotide) (+1). 4. Alternative causes: Patient was on a chemotherapy regimen (vincristine, actinomycin-D); however, cyclophosphamide is a known agent for SOS. Given the established association, a score of 6 (Probable) is assigned. The event is considered Expected as it is explicitly mentioned in section 5.6 of the RSI.

