The patient experienced multiple cerebral arterial thromboembolism (ATE) while receiving edoxaban for VTE. The narrative explicitly states the patient was diagnosed with Trousseau syndrome due to lung cancer progression and increased coagulation, providing a clear alternative etiology. Edoxaban is an anticoagulant; while its efficacy for arterial thrombosis is debated, it is biologically implausible for an anticoagulant to directly cause an arterial thromboembolic event; the event is more likely related to the underlying hypercoagulable state of malignancy. Naranjo scoring: -1 (alternative cause present), +1 (temporal relationship exists), -1 (no dechallenge effect as the patient was switched to another anticoagulant due to disease progression), leading to a score of 0 or less. The event is a serious medical event (cerebral ATE is a life-threatening or disabling condition). As the RSI for edoxaban focuses on bleeding risks and VTE treatment, cerebral ATE is not listed as an expected adverse reaction of the drug itself, but rather a potential failure of efficacy for an off-label indication in this specific context of malignancy-associated hypercoagulability.

